    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-15T21:34:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-15T21:34:00-05:00" n="381"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d381">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/448</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the Advisory Commission of Railway Experts to
                        Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SJF1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stevens</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Harbin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-16T11:00:00+08:26">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 16, 1918, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.35 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_ECH1">Emerson</persName> reports from near Irkutsk where
                    he and men are cooperating with Czechs repairing bridges blown up by enemy. He
                    did not get west of Urals and never in touch with American Ambassador.<note
                        n="1" xml:id="d381fn1">For reports of his efforts to mediate between the
                        Czecho-Slovaks and Bolsheviks, see <ref target="frus1918Russiav02#pg_191"
                            >vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, pp. 191</ref> and <ref
                            target="frus1918Russiav02#pg_212">212</ref>.</note> Czechs’ east front
                    is at south end Lake Baikal, west from Orenburg, Samara, Ekaterinburg, Tyumen.
                    Please advise families <pb facs="0289" n="239" xml:id="pg_239"/>
                    <persName corresp="#p_ECH1">Emerson</persName>, <persName>Hawkins</persName>,
                        <persName>Johnson</persName>, <persName>Haynes</persName>,
                        <persName>Bjonerud</persName>, location party, apparently all are well.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stevens</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
